#DESCRIPTION: 
  #Runs base and counterfactual DPM models from a command line prompt (or from the desktop INIT.xlsx file) and creates output files summarizing model results.

#DEVELOPMENT NOTES: 
   #Currently written to handle one alternative product. Additional work will be needed if model structure changes.

#------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#FILE DEPENDENCIES: 
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------

#RDPM Model Specification Excel File:
      #RDPM reads this file to determine how to run the model. Follow proper naming conventions for this file (see RDPM web tool administrator for details).

#Supporting Files: RDPM Requires several supporting files, all of which  must be placed in the same diretory as RDPM.r:
  #0) StartRDPM.r: This is an initialization script for calling RDPM and associated files and managing batch run operations in the desktop version.
  #1) PathWalk.r: This contains the algorithm for calculating the survival curves. 
  #2) TransitionProb.r: Contains a function definition to convert transition probability format in the specification spreadsheet to a set of transition matrices for use by PathWalk.r
  #3) Output Module.r: This formats the output from PathWalk to summarize results by scenario, state, and time period.
  #4) TM_Plot.r: Creates a transition diagram to facilitate checking the accuracy of the model's structure.

#------------------------------------------------------------------------------  
#RDPM SCRIPT: SEQUENCE OF OPERATIONS
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------

  #1) Load required library files [done in StartRDPM.r]
  #2) Read and check command line arguments [done in StartRDPM.r]
  #3) Read model specification .xlsx file 
  #4) Set up model parameters (number of runs, start age, age category widths, relative risks, transition probabilities, paramater variances, etc.) 
  #5) Set up Base Case and Counterfactual Scenario data arrays (to hold survival curves for each behavior state) and transition matrices
  #6) Load appropriate mortality function coefficients (betas)
  #7) Run base case/counterfactual simulations and store results. RDPM does this sequentially since PathWalk relies on two "globally" defined strctures: Pt and Tr for the survival curves and transition probabilities, respectively. Thus, base case results need to be copied to other variables and then Pt and Tr are redefined to get ready for the counterfactual scenario.
  #8) Send results to output module to create the data file of summary statistics.
  #9) Create results file and session log and save to appropriate results file.
   
